big fallacy of VR is to think that seeing is immersion. it’s not. the scope of possible experiences is far narrower than your imagination would suggest. 1/n

when you see a picture of a situation, you have a background assumption the subjects can interact with their environment and each other. they can walk together, bump into each other, etc. it’s obvious, taken for granted. 2/n https://i.imgur.com/0XgwXdp.jpg

when you see a depiction of VR, you make the same assumption, but it’s wildly wrong. mobility is virtually impossible, nothing is subject to touch, and you can’t even experience acceleration in a vehicle. your background assumptions are broken in a fundamental way. 3/n https://i.imgur.com/QNZlKa8.jpg

it gets worse with telepresence because the subject who’s in your space can’t actually see your environment, and you can’t see theirs. that’s why movies never show you what the other participants see. unless they have an identical room with identical (empty) chairs, it doesn’t work. 4/n https://i.imgur.com/3B

so doing something simple like saying “hey, what do you think of this new couch?” doesn’t work. you see them in your space, but they don’t see your couch. they don’t see your dog over your shoulder. they see their space. 5/n

it’s all broken background assumptions. the promise (or hype) of this space depends on hand waving the details of how visual virtual presence works. the imagination goes to teleportation, but it’s not that. temper expectations. 6/n, n=6
